<h2>What is Swagbucks?</h2>
<p>Swagbucks is one of the largest and oldest rewards platforms, with over 20 million users and $800+ million paid out since 2008. It's owned by Prodege, a legitimate advertising company. You earn "Swagbucks" (SB) for completing tasks, and 100 SB equals $1.</p>

<h2>How Does It Work?</h2>
<p>Swagbucks offers a wide range of earning methods:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Surveys</strong> — the main earner, pays 50-300 SB per survey</li>
  <li><strong>Discover Offers</strong> — sign up for services, download apps, play games</li>
  <li><strong>Watch Videos</strong> — low pay but passive</li>
  <li><strong>Shopping Cashback</strong> — earn SB on purchases at 1,500+ stores</li>
  <li><strong>Search</strong> — use Swagbucks search engine for random SB rewards</li>
  <li><strong>SwagButton</strong> — browser extension that finds cashback deals automatically</li>
</ul>

<h2>Gaming on Swagbucks</h2>
<p>The gaming offers are in the "Discover" section. You'll find similar offers to FreeCash — reach a certain level in a mobile game, earn SB. However, the payouts tend to be slightly lower than FreeCash for the same offers, since Swagbucks takes a larger cut.</p>
<p>Where Swagbucks does well is daily goals and streaks. Hit your daily earning target consistently and you get bonus SB. This gamification of the platform itself keeps you engaged.</p>

<h2>The Points System</h2>
<p>The biggest annoyance with Swagbucks is the points currency. Everything is in "SB" instead of dollars, which makes it harder to quickly assess the value of an offer. When a survey says "150 SB," you have to mentally convert that to $1.50. It's a psychological trick to make offers seem more valuable than they are.</p>

<h2>Where Swagbucks Excels</h2>
<p>If you do a lot of online shopping, Swagbucks' cashback feature is genuinely useful. The SwagButton browser extension automatically alerts you to cashback opportunities at stores like Amazon, Walmart, and Target. This passive earning adds up over time without any extra effort.</p>

<h2>Our Verdict</h2>
<p>Swagbucks is a solid all-around platform, but it's not the best at any single thing. FreeCash beats it on gaming offer payouts and cashout minimums. InboxDollars is simpler to use. Where Swagbucks shines is the breadth of options and the shopping cashback. Good as a secondary platform in your earning rotation.</p>

